<article id="post-752" class="post-752 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-uncategorized">
	<header class="entry-header">
					<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="https://iamcat.blog/confining-a-cat-or-not/" rel="bookmark">Do I confine my cat or not?</a></h1>		
				<div class="entry-meta">
						<span class="posted-on"><a href="https://iamcat.blog/confining-a-cat-or-not/" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date published" datetime="2023-01-15T06:52:11+00:00">January 15, 2023</time><time class="updated" datetime="2023-01-15T06:52:20+00:00">January 15, 2023</time></a></span><span class="byline"> <span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="https://iamcat.blog/author/anneke/">anneke</a></span></span>		</div><!-- .entry-meta -->

			</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	<div class="entry-content">
		
<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Cat Blog 10</h2>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Confining a cat or not</h2>



<p>Like me you&#8217;ve probably been thinking about whether or not you should somehow be confining your cats. I have no definitive answer about confining a cat or not either, but I thought I could present you with some of the pros and cons. And perhaps you could send me your thoughts as well to add interest to the debate. Together we will figure it out and even begin formulating some guidelines.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Catios</h2>



<p>I can think of a few cons regarding the use of catios:</p>



<ul>
<li>Many cat lovers feel strongly that their cats should have complete freedom to live as nature intended them to live.</li>



<li>They also worry that their cats will become bored in confinement, and may even acquire one of the disorders that understimulated cats can develop.</li>



<li>Some of us can&#8217;t afford the cost of having a catio built or a cat-proof fence erected.</li>



<li>Apartment dwellers may feel that they simply don&#8217;t have the required space.</li>
</ul>



<p></p>


<div class="wp-block-image">
<figure class="aligncenter size-full is-resized"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" src="https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Catios-for-apartments.jpg?resize=527%2C395&#038;ssl=1" alt="Catio for apartment living" class="wp-image-757" width="527" height="395" data-recalc-dims="1" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><strong>Catio for apartment living</strong></figcaption></figure></div>


<p>According to Alan Breslauer, aka The Catio Guy and owner of Custom Catios in Los Angeles, there are even more pros (<a href="https://pasadenahumane.org/5-benefits-to-investing-in-a-catio/">https://pasadenahumane.org/5-benefits-to-investing-in-a-catio/</a>):</p>



<p></p>



<p></p>



<figure class="wp-block-gallery has-nested-images columns-default is-cropped wp-block-gallery-6 is-layout-flex wp-block-gallery-is-layout-flex">
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="634" height="389" data-id="754" src="https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Catio-small.png?resize=634%2C389&#038;ssl=1" alt="Small catio" class="wp-image-754" srcset="https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Catio-small.png?w=634&amp;ssl=1 634w, https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Catio-small.png?resize=300%2C184&amp;ssl=1 300w" sizes="(max-width: 634px) 100vw, 634px" data-recalc-dims="1" /></figure>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="283" height="178" data-id="755" src="https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Catio-large.jpg?resize=283%2C178&#038;ssl=1" alt="Large catio" class="wp-image-755" data-recalc-dims="1"/></figure>
</figure>



<p>Images: Metairie Small Animal Hospital, New Orleans</p>



<p></p>



<ul>
<li>The health and safety of the cats, which are probably self-evident. Cats that are confined are not exposed to cars, dogs, cat fights, irate humans or poison. Breslauer cites Jackson Galaxy in referring to catios as &#8216;the great compromise&#8217;, allowing cats &#8216;to have access to fresh air and sunshine, to see birds and bugs, and to experience a little bit of what comes with outdoor living&#8217;.
<ul></ul>
</li>



<li>Breslauer also mentions the fact that human cat companions tend to sleep better when their furballs have access to the outdoors at dawn.</li>



<li>In addition litter boxes can be moved outdoors, which cats seem to prefer in any event.</li>



<li>And then a biggie: protecting wildlife. Estimates of the number of birds and small mammals killed by cats tend to be wildly exaggerated. However, it stands to reason that cats that can only watch wildlife from a safe distance cannot add to the number of prey.</li>
</ul>



<p></p>


<div class="wp-block-image">
<figure class="aligncenter size-full is-resized"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" src="https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Catios-2.jpg?resize=620%2C443&#038;ssl=1" alt="Cat in catio with sea view" class="wp-image-756" width="620" height="443" data-recalc-dims="1" /></figure></div>


<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Fencing</h2>



<p>I think most of us would prefer to keep our cats on our premises &#8211; especially if we have ample space. Cat guardians the world over make use of a number of different methods to achieve this:</p>



<p>Roller-type fencing such as the Australian Oscillot (<a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=i-8x22Ce55I&amp;feature=endscreen&amp;NR=1">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=i-8x22Ce55I&amp;feature=endscreen&amp;NR=1</a>). If you live in Gauteng, Morné from Pet Safety Solutions (079 045 6185 or <a href="http://petsafetysolutions.co.za/">http://petsafetysolutions.co.za</a>) will be able to install this – and any other safety system – for you. (See more on them in Cat story 15 below.)</p>



<div class="wp-block-media-text alignwide is-stacked-on-mobile"><figure class="wp-block-media-text__media"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="660" height="528" src="https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Oscillot-1.jpg?resize=660%2C528&#038;ssl=1" alt="The Oscillot fence" class="wp-image-759 size-full" srcset="https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Oscillot-1.jpg?w=800&amp;ssl=1 800w, https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Oscillot-1.jpg?resize=300%2C240&amp;ssl=1 300w, https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Oscillot-1.jpg?resize=768%2C614&amp;ssl=1 768w" sizes="(max-width: 660px) 100vw, 660px" data-recalc-dims="1" /></figure><div class="wp-block-media-text__content">
<p>Roller-type fencing such as the Australian Oscillot (<a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=i-8x22Ce55I&amp;feature=endscreen&amp;NR=1">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=i-8x22Ce55I&amp;feature=endscreen&amp;NR=1</a>). If you live in Gauteng, Morné from Pet Safety Solutions (079 045 6185 or <a href="http://petsafetysolutions.co.za/">http://petsafetysolutions.co.za</a>) will be able to install this – and any other safety system – for you.</p>
</div></div>



<p></p>



<p></p>



<p></p>


<div class="wp-block-image">
<figure class="alignright size-full"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="520" height="275" src="https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/pet-stop-solar-powered-kit-7258-lg.jpg?resize=520%2C275&#038;ssl=1" alt="PetStop solar kit" class="wp-image-760" srcset="https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/pet-stop-solar-powered-kit-7258-lg.jpg?w=520&amp;ssl=1 520w, https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/pet-stop-solar-powered-kit-7258-lg.jpg?resize=300%2C159&amp;ssl=1 300w" sizes="(max-width: 520px) 100vw, 520px" data-recalc-dims="1" /></figure></div>


<p>Alternatively you could install something like the Pet Stop solar-powered kit along your fence (<a href="https://www.nemtek.co.za/equineandpet/Pet-Systems/pet-stop-solar-powered-kit.aspx">https://www.nemtek.co.za/equineandpet/Pet-Systems/pet-stop-solar-powered-kit.aspx</a>).</p>



<p></p>



<p></p>



<p></p>



<div class="wp-block-media-text alignwide is-stacked-on-mobile"><figure class="wp-block-media-text__media"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="329" height="245" src="https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Netting-to-confine-cats.jpg?resize=329%2C245&#038;ssl=1" alt="Netting to confine cats" class="wp-image-761 size-full" srcset="https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Netting-to-confine-cats.jpg?w=329&amp;ssl=1 329w, https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Netting-to-confine-cats.jpg?resize=300%2C223&amp;ssl=1 300w" sizes="(max-width: 329px) 100vw, 329px" data-recalc-dims="1" /></figure><div class="wp-block-media-text__content">
<p>Another option is unobtrusive netting. This kind of netting is available from e.g. Bird Control&nbsp; in Somerset West, 021 300 1623, or from Pet Safety Solutions in Gauteng (see contact details above and/or Cat Story 15 below).</p>
</div></div>



<p></p>



<p></p>


<div class="wp-block-image">
<figure class="alignright size-full is-resized"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" src="https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Non-electrified-cat-fencing.jpg?resize=446%2C335&#038;ssl=1" alt="Non-electrified cat fencing" class="wp-image-763" width="446" height="335" srcset="https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Non-electrified-cat-fencing.jpg?w=328&amp;ssl=1 328w, https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Non-electrified-cat-fencing.jpg?resize=300%2C225&amp;ssl=1 300w" sizes="(max-width: 446px) 100vw, 446px" data-recalc-dims="1" /></figure></div>


<p>Non-electrified fencing bent inwards, wires closely spaced, keep cats inside property. (You could use a greater inward angle to make it more difficult for cats to negotiate.)</p>



<p></p>



<p></p>



<p></p>



<p></p>



<p></p>



<div style="height:100px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>



<p></p>



<p></p>



<div class="wp-block-media-text alignwide is-stacked-on-mobile"><figure class="wp-block-media-text__media"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="327" height="245" src="https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Plastic-bottles-wrapped-around-tree.jpg?resize=327%2C245&#038;ssl=1" alt="Plastic bottles wrapped around trees to prevent cats escaping" class="wp-image-764 size-full" srcset="https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Plastic-bottles-wrapped-around-tree.jpg?w=327&amp;ssl=1 327w, https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Plastic-bottles-wrapped-around-tree.jpg?resize=300%2C225&amp;ssl=1 300w" sizes="(max-width: 327px) 100vw, 327px" data-recalc-dims="1" /></figure><div class="wp-block-media-text__content">
<p>A particularly clever trick to keep cats from escaping from your property by climbing trees is wrapping plastic bottles that have been cut open around the trees.</p>
</div></div>



<p></p>



<p>So in conclusion, what are your thoughts about confining your cats &#8211; or not? I would love to hear from you!</p>



<p></p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Cat quote of the week</h2>



<p></p>



<figure class="wp-block-pullquote"><blockquote><p>         Cats are connoisseurs of comfort.</p><cite>James Herriot</cite></blockquote></figure>



<p></p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Cat Story 15: Pet Safety Solutions, Gauteng</h2>



<p>Five years ago, in 2018, Morné Combrink decided that he wanted to commit himself to helping pet owners keep their pets safe. And so Pet Safety Solutions was born, and their slogan says it all: &#8216;Their safety is our concern&#8217;.</p>



<p></p>


<div class="wp-block-image">
<figure class="aligncenter size-large is-resized"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" src="https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Lobo-PSS.jpg?resize=537%2C205&#038;ssl=1" alt="Logo Pet Safety Solutions" class="wp-image-768" width="537" height="205" srcset="https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Lobo-PSS.jpg?resize=1024%2C392&amp;ssl=1 1024w, https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Lobo-PSS.jpg?resize=300%2C115&amp;ssl=1 300w, https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Lobo-PSS.jpg?resize=768%2C294&amp;ssl=1 768w, https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Lobo-PSS.jpg?resize=1536%2C588&amp;ssl=1 1536w, https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Lobo-PSS.jpg?w=1571&amp;ssl=1 1571w, https://i0.wp.com/iamcat.blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Lobo-PSS.jpg?w=1320&amp;ssl=1 1320w" sizes="(max-width: 537px) 100vw, 537px" data-recalc-dims="1" /></figure></div>


<p></p>



<p>He was more qualified than most for the job. In addition to having all the necessary skills to do the job, he had been supporting partner Charlene in her tireless work with community (feral) cats in Pretoria for many years. He was also the long-time Chairperson of the Pretoria based NPO Be Wise Sterilise.</p>



<p>But nothing tells us more about Morné than the long record of imaginative and meticulous work he has done at the homes of countless pet owners, mostly in Gauteng and the Western Cape but also further afield.</p>



<p></p>



<figure class="wp-block-gallery has-nested-images columns-default is-cropped wp-block-gallery-7 is-layout-flex wp-block-gallery-is-layout-flex">
